SIMPLE: connoisseur
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Connoisseur
<hw>Con`nois*seur"</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>connaisseur</ets>, formerly <ets>connoisseur</ets>, fr.
<ets>conna⟦icir⟧tre</ets> to know, fr. L. <ets>cognoscere</ets> to
become acquainted with; <ets>co-</ets> + <ets>noscere</ets>,
<ets>gnoscere</ets>, to learn to know. See <er>Know</er>, and cf.
<er>Cognizor</er>.]</ety> <def>One well versed in any subject; a
skillful or knowing person; a critical judge of any art, particularly of
one of the fine arts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>connoisseur</qex> is ⟦ldquo⟧one who knows,⟦rdquo⟧ as
opposed to the dilettant, who only ⟦ldquo⟧thinks he knows.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Fairholt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Connoisseurship</ent>⟦br⟧
